In my case, I have a total of 12 sessions spanning 9/6 - 9/25

Informational only (dont need to include)

# Look at days with 1 or more sessions

# summarize to show the *number of sessions* by date and hour-of-day. 
df = ga_datadf %>%
  subset(sessions > 0) %>%
  group_by(date, hour)  %>%
  summarize(sessions)

df
## # A tibble: 9 x 3
## # Groups:   date [6]
##   date        hour sessions
##   <date>     <int>    <int>
## 1 2020-09-06    14        3
## 2 2020-09-06    15        1
## 3 2020-09-06    16        1
## 4 2020-09-06    17        1
## 5 2020-09-08    19        1
## 6 2020-09-19    16        2
## 7 2020-09-23    13        1
## 8 2020-09-24    16        1
## 9 2020-09-25    23        1
# contingency table that shows the days that have at least 1 session
addmargins(with(df, table(date, sessions, dnn = c('date', 'sessions'))))
##             sessions
## date         1 2 3 Sum
##   2020-09-06 3 0 1   4

# filter by session on 9/6 to confirm that 9/16 has 6 sessions
ga_datadf  %>%
  filter(date=='2020-09-06' & sessions > 0) %>%
  summarize(date, hour, sessions)
##         date hour sessions
## 1 2020-09-06   14        3
## 2 2020-09-06   15        1
## 3 2020-09-06   16        1
## 4 2020-09-06   17        1

Explanation

  • 9/6 has a total of 6 sessions. (3) 1 sessions and (1) 3 sessions. This can be confirmed by looking at the Audience Overview in GA and filtering by specific date
  • 9/19 has (2) sessions
  • all other dates have just (1) sessions each.
  • Total number of sessions for the last 30 days is is 12
  • Filter by session on 9/6 to confirm that 9/16 has 6 sessions
